<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-255-575  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 255 575.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Jan 1989 v62 n1 p91(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Under the gun at the Pentagon. (military and governmentelectronics spending)andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Electronic Industries Association expects defense spending todrop by two percent until 1994, then continue growth at a rateless than 0.5 percent per year as a result of the increasingfederal deficit.andP;  Government spending for electronics will bereduced by about two percent to $46.8 billion in 1989, yetelectronics will account for over 43 percent of the overalldefense budget by 1998.andP;  The Department of Defense will suffer thecuts in every sector, with a few exceptions such as spending formilitary space applications, which is expected to grow fivepercent in 1989.andP;  The non-defense areas will have cutbacks also,but NASA will increase its spending on information technology by15 percent in 1989 for a total of $1.26 billion, and theDepartment of the Treasury will spend $1.29 billion.andP;  Othergovernment spending forecasts are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     National GovernmentBudgetingGrowthForecastingElectronic Industry.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraphtable.andO;Caption:   Military spending for electronics 1987-1998. (graph)Military equipment sales 1987-1989. (table)Federal equipment sales 1987-1989. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>